{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure boundary is OS/filesystem watcher recursion behavior. A mock watcher can emit a nested-path event and falsely pass even if real recursive watch wiring is broken (MOCK-HIDE, REAL-INFRA). Rejected Integration because behavior text requires actual watched-directory behavior for subdirectories, not just in-process handoff logic.","test_description":"Run the daemon against real temporary input/output directories, create a real subdirectory under the watched root, write a file into that subdirectory, and assert the transformed output is produced once in output without restarting the daemon.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is a local rule (same path + time window) and can fail inside one dedup component with a controllable clock. No OS/network/subprocess dependency is required by the behavior text, and no LLM dependency exists. Rejected Integration because no module handoff is needed to expose this specific failure.","test_description":"Unit-test the dedup function/object with a fake clock: first request for path is accepted, second within window is rejected, and a later request after window is accepted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.76,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on real OS multi-event emission for one write (REAL-INFRA). In-process fakes usually emit idealized events and can hide duplicate-event races (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected Integration because the failure trigger is the operating system event pattern itself.","test_description":"Start daemon with real watcher, perform a write pattern that generates multiple events (e.g., chunked write and close/rename), and assert downstream processing is invoked exactly once for that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.11,"System":0.88,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is an inode/path lifecycle and watcher re-subscription problem tied to real filesystem semantics (REAL-INFRA). Mocked watchers can bypass the true remove/recreate edge and miss real breakage (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected Integration because behavior text requires live daemon recovery from real directory deletion/recreation.","test_description":"Run daemon watching a real directory, delete that directory while running, recreate it at the same path, then add a new file and verify it is processed without restarting the daemon.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.95,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Minimum failure boundary is local module wiring: intake -> metadata lookup -> ordering queue. This can be reproduced in-process by injecting concurrent arrivals and controlled creation timestamps. Integration-brake check: no required real OS/network/subprocess contract in the behavior text, no AI/ML dependency, no multi-agentic chain. Rejected System because behavior text focuses on ordering rule by creation timestamp, which can be validated through in-process module handoff/state.","test_description":"Integration test the real pipeline modules in-process with a fake watcher/input adapter that emits same-time arrivals and a metadata provider returning different creation timestamps; assert processing occurs in timestamp order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Correctness depends on real filesystem write timing and event sequencing while a file handle is still active (REAL-INFRA). A mock write/close sequence can hide partial-write races and premature pickup bugs (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected Integration because behavior text is explicitly about in-progress OS-level writes at event time.","test_description":"Run daemon with real watcher, begin writing a large file via a slow stream so arrival event occurs before close, assert no processing starts during active write, then close stream and assert processing starts afterward.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
